Triumph of right-wing populists in Austria, they have a total of 29 percent
According to the preliminary results, the early parliamentary elections in Austria led to a significant weakening of the two parties forming the current major coalition, as well as a notorious strengthening of the populist parties.
The Austrian People's Party (ÖVP), where the position of current President Wilhelm Molterer is seriously threatened, suffered from particularly large losses.
On the other hand, the electoral leader of the Union for the Future of Austria (BZÖ), the governor of Carinthia Jörg Haider, is preparing a triumphal return to the national political scene.
According to preliminary results, the Socialists (SPÖ) remain, with 29.8 percent of the vote, the country's first political force, however, compared to the 2006 elections, they lost 5.5 percent of the vote.
The ÖVP, which with 25.6 per cent lost almost nine per cent of the votes, ended even worse.
These are the worst results of the two major post-war parties; especially for the popular party, which launched the early elections, the result is literally catastrophic.
At the beginning of July, when the ÖVP left the coalition, the popular party had a considerable advance on the SPÖ.
However, voters visibly punished them for letting the government collapse.
From the first reactions to the results, speculations were made about the possible resignation of the party leader and the current vice-chancellor Wilhelm Molterer.
Observers believe that this could happen as early as Monday, during the extraordinary leadership council of the party.
Such an evolution would a priori facilitate the path towards the outcome of the election, which remains the most likely, namely the renewal of the large SPÖ and ÖVP coalition.
Nevertheless, given the strengthening of the two right-wing populist parties - the free (FPÖ) would have obtained 18 per cent and BZÖ 11 per cent of the votes - the Socialists at the same time expressed the fear of a repetition of 1999, when the popular party agreed with the populists (at the time, the FPÖ was still unified, it was in 2005 that the BZÖ separated from it) on a common government, which even raised sanctions on the part of the European Union.
Haider, who has already stated that he is ready to work with any party and that he plans to return to Vienna, on the national political scene, apparently relies on this evolution.
The last party to have access to the parliament being the Greens, but they slightly lost and fell, among the Austrian political parties, from the third to the fifth.
Obviously, no other party crossed the four-per-cent limit and entered parliament.
Schwarzenberg: Relations with India at Risk of Cooling
If the problem of Czech researchers accused in India of illegally collecting cockroaches could not be resolved, a certain cooling of Czech-Indian relations would follow, according to Czech Foreign Minister Karel Schwarzenberg.
The minister declared it today in New York, after meeting his Indian counterpart Pranab Mukherjee.
"If the problem was not resolved, then yes, some cooling would occur," he observed after the meeting, carried out following a Czech initiative.
Mukherjee said, after the talks, that the executive branch could hardly intervene in judicial matters.
However, he mentioned that in the case of Petr Švácha, who was discharged from the charge and punished by a fine, the central government could negotiate with the local government, that of the Darjeling, the case being placed under its jurisdiction.
"His problem could be solved," said the minister.
According to Mukherjee, the best solution for Emil Kučera, sentenced to three years in prison, would be to appeal to a higher court.
Therefore, he could request bail and wait for the trial to be released, he explained.
Schwarzenberg confirmed, that his partner expressed himself in the same direction also during the talks.
"He advises to appeal to a higher court, after which he could be pardoned," said the head of Czech diplomacy.
The only way in which the Czech side can intervene in this case is to provide the convicted with "competent legal support", mentioned the Indian Minister.
He also said that such assistance was already being provided to them by India.
"We want above all to keep with India the best relations, which have a tradition continuing over many years.
The Indians also recognize it," said Schwarzenberg.
At the same time, as he said to ČTK, he stressed to his partner that the Czech Republic attached great importance to the problem of Czech entomologies.
"We regard the imprisonment and accusation of these Czech researchers as a great contempt," he said.
The minister shunned the question whether he had obtained a promise from India to deal with the matter.
"I've already received quite a lot of promises," he said.
