Turkey is expanding its diplomatic horizons.
Long before Turkey planned to join the European Union, the European powers were eager to enter its hinterland.
On the east side of the Bosphorus, 20 steps from Asia, is one of the finest relics of its fallen imperial ambition.
The Hydarpasha railway station was designed in a neo-renaissance style by two German architects, Otto Ritter and Helmut Conu.
At least that's what the guides tell us.
The monument is arranged on horseback at the bottom of the platforms, equipped with observation tower at each of its angles, like some German provincial townships.
The stones are dirty.
The whole building is ruined.
But once inside the vaulted ticket office, we have no more doubt as to the size of the company, which represents a passage to the west.
The station was inaugurated in August 1908 by a German association, Anatolia-Baghdad Corporation.
Germany, a retard in the game of imperialism, wanted to realize its medieval ambitions of domination thanks to this railway that arrives in Damascus, Baghdad as well as has the land better known as Saudi Arabia.
But German imperialist ambitions collapsed during World War I.
His railways were attacked by Lawrence of Arabia and his Arab irregulars.
The relative isolation of its surrounding region, generated by the icy borders of the Cold War, is over.
. The British and the forces of the empire advanced beyond Egypt and pushed the Turks and their German allies out of Palestine and Syria.
But there was also bad news for Hyderpasha station.
In 1917, a train loaded with ammunition exploded destroying its subtle roof.
Turkish sources say this is a sabotage.
Since then, it has slowly fallen to ruin, swallowed up in the meanders of history.
But today, the rail crossing to Anatolia and all the eastern points, at least symbolically, serves to highlight the enlargement of Turkey's diplomatic horizons.
The ruling Justice and Development Party, the AKP, has created a new foreign policy for the country.
The relative isolation of its surrounding region, generated by the icy borders of the Cold War
Now is the time for a new commitment policy.
The Turkish government has remarkable relations with Israel and Syria, the Palestinian factions of Hamas and Fatah, Iran and Iraq, and of course with the European Union and the United States.
To judge the parameters of this new foreign policy, I embarked on a bed-car towards the Turkish capital, Ankara, to visit the Turkish MP AKP Suat Kinikioglu, one of the experts in foreign policy.
The next morning, after a journey of 10 and a half hours, shaken on noisy rails whose cadence reminded the old world of the famous documentary The Night Mail, I finally arrived in the Turkish capital - presented as a new city of a new secular state, turning my back on its German past.
But the AKP with its well-known Islamist roots is an example of a change in Turkish consensus.
He suspected the West, and particularly in Washington.
A taxi accompanied me to the AKP headquarters, an ultra-modern structure, specifically made of stones and steel, in a developing neighborhood, surrounded by half-built shopping centres and numerous pastry shops where middle managers in costume-tie-men and women- meet for morning business.
Suat Kiniklioglu could have been a centre-right politician from any other party in Europe.
Costume, tie, and he even has a Black Berry.
" the aim of this foreign policy is now to reintegrate Turkey into its immediate neighbourhood.
The Cold War was an anomaly," he said.
Turkey was cut off from its hind country.
Now she has to look east and west at the same time.
It wasn't the case with each other.
She had to do both.
"but, at some point, I asked if" Turkey should choose?"
"Turkey," he said, "doesn't want to have to choose between the two."
He then pointed out one aspect that almost everyone I was able to talk to, recited to me by heart: The Turkish railway does not only go to the Middle East, but also to the Caucasus, and around the Black Sea, it is therefore, as much an advantage for Europe and the United States as for Turkey itself.
With the integration of Turkey, the message seems to draw a Europe that is travelling metaphorically on the rails to Asia and the Middle East.
Back at Hydarpasha Station, after another sleepless night, I thought about these two Germans, Herr Ritter and Herr Conu, who followed the construction of this building 100 years ago.
They would have been surprised to see that the European ambitions of the Middle East could, to a large extent, be in the hands of Turkey.
