The 'bee car' that avoids collisions
In order to advance the development of accident prevention technologies, Nissan was inspired this time by nature, especially bees.
The Japanese company has created a robot that, by imitating the theft of bees, avoids accidents.
It is called Bio-Mimetic Car Robot Drive, or BR23C and represents the first steps towards collision prevention technologies.
The engineers of Nissan Motor Co.'s Advanced Technical Centre made this small robot in collaboration with the Centre for Advanced Science and Technology Research at the prestigious University of Tokyo, Japan.
According to Kazuhiro Doi, the Director General of Public Relations for Technology and Research and Brand Management Development, the BR23C represents the development of the Nissan security shield.
This robot will allow branded vehicles to prevent collisions.
During its flight, each bee creates its own personal space in an oval shape that looks a lot like the Nissan security shield.
But the most important thing is the eyes composed of the bee, able to see in an angle of more than 300 degrees and in all directions, which allows it to fly without interruption inside its own personal space.
To recreate this visual function, engineers have developed what is called a laser locator (Laser Range Finder).
It detects obstacles within a distance of two metres and within a radius of 180 degrees, calculates the distance to this object and sends a signal to the microprocessor immediately to avoid the obstacle.
"When it detects an obstacle, the small robot will mimic the movements of a bee and immediately change direction by bifurcating its wheels 90 degrees or more to avoid collision.
The biggest difference from any other existing system is that the escape maneuver is totally instinctive.
If this were the case, the robot would not be able to react quickly enough to avoid the obstacles," explains Toshiyuki Andoh, director of the Moving Laboratory and chief engineer of this project.
Unlike a bee, the robot cannot be turned upwards or downwards, nor diagonally; it can only move in two dimensions and according to what its wheels allow it and not in infinite directions such as bees.
For this reason, Nissan used a rotational function, but also acceleration and deceleration, so that the small robot can avoid obstacles.
" Every second this device should only process information and act on it.
It does not need to keep the information or intuitive logics of previous maneuvers, which is why it can work continuously with only a few dozen KB of memory.
This may surprise you, but we're not talking about gigabytes of memory or even megabytes."
This represents the first development of new technologies for the instantaneous prevention of collisions, a technology that will be introduced in standard cars in about ten years according to Nissan.
The robot works with lithium-polymer batteries, which are lighter and last longer than lithium-ion batteries.
The other possible application of this technology in the future could be the adaptation of this device on a GPS satellite navigation system to guide the driver to his destination by avoiding obstacles on the road.
