Rafael Correa in Quito this Monday.
Recast the republic around the socialism of the twenty-first century.
This is the joint project of Venezuelan Hugo Chávez, Bolivian Evo Morales and Ecuadorian Rafael Correa.
This Sunday, like his colleagues and friends, he was the third to vote on a draft new Constitution.
Mission accomplished since 64% of voters voted "yes" in the referendum, according to official results covering 80% of the votes.
According to these results, the "no" obtained 28%, 7% of the votes were null and 0.7% were white votes.
In order for the draft Constitution to be adopted, it had to obtain half of the votes plus one.
On Sunday, two polls conducted at the exit of the polling stations and a count of a non-governmental organization had announced a large "yes" victory, between 63% and 70%.
Rafael Correa had claimed the victory of his draft Constitution on the night of Sunday to Monday.
The "Constitution triumphed overwhelmingly", he assured, congratulating the Ecuadorians at the headquarters of the governorate of Guayaquil, 280 kilometers southwest of Quito.
As of course, Rafael Correa was congratulated by Chávez and Morales but also his Chilean counterpart Michelle Bachelet.
The election, which took place calmly according to the observation mission of the Organization of American States (OAS), focused on a text in 444 points consolidating the "new socialism" defended by the president.
The draft Constitution enshrines the power of the State over the economy, reserving to it the "planning of development" of a country living mainly from the extraction of oil by foreign companies and the currencies sent by its emigrants.
Brought by Correa, elected in 2006, the project also grants strengthened powers to the Head of State, who will be able to carry out up to two consecutive terms of four years and will have the opportunity to dissolve the Assembly.
Correa has already announced that it will use this power and fight for a new mandate in February 2009.
The Constitution further consolidates the principle of free health and education services that the President has begun to establish in this country of 13.9 million inhabitants, where 50% of the population lives below the poverty line.
Finally, it provides for a ban on the presence of foreign troops, which will put an end to the agreement between Quito and Washington for the use of an Ecuadorian base as a starting point for US anti-drug operations.
The 19 hostages were released in Chad
An Egyptian commando launched the assault on the kidnappers of the eleven tourists and their eight escorts captured ten days ago.
They're in Cairo.
The eleven European tourists and their eight Egyptian escorts held captive for ten days in the desert were brought back this Monday afternoon safe and sound in the Egyptian capital.
In the morning, they had been released by an Egyptian commando in Chad.
Apparently in good shape, the hostages arrived at approximately 3:30 p.m. on a special plane at the al-Maza military base, located at Cairo International Airport.
They were immediately transferred, without being able to speak to the press, aboard helicopters to Maadi Hospital, a residential suburb of Cairo, for examination.
They are in "good health", and "no ransom has been paid" to the kidnappers," Egyptian Minister of Tourism Zoheir Garanna said on the tarmac.
Captured on 19 September during a 4x4 safari at the foot of Mount Ouanat, on the borders of Egypt, Sudan and Libya, this group of hostages had been swept from one cache to another by 35 unknown kidnappers.
It includes 11 tourists - five Italians, five Germans and one Romanian - as well as eight Egyptians: two guides, four drivers, a border guard and the director of the agency Aegyptous, organizer of the safari.
An Egyptian security officer reported that 30 Special Forces personnel, transported on board two helicopters, had launched the attack in the night just before dawn.
"An exchange of fire occurred, and half of the kidnappers were killed, the others fleeing," said the official who requested anonymity.
He reported that 150 members of the Egyptian special forces of the "light" unit had been sent to Sudan, where they were supported by German and Italian commandos.
The head of Italian diplomacy Franco Frattini mentioned Belgrade, where he is, the role played by secret agents and elements of the Italian special forces.
"We must recognize that we have achieved this result thanks to the professionalism and efficiency of our men in the secret services, special forces," he said, without further details.
He also denied the payment of a ransom.
The previous day, the Sudanese army claimed that it had intercepted a 4x4 vehicle on which the kidnappers were on board, killing in six, including the Chadian leader, and arresting two.
The army had claimed that they were linked to a rebel group in Darfur, the Sudan-Unit Liberation Movement (SLA-U), which the movement immediately denied.
