Benelux governments nationalize part of Fortis Bank
The Benelux states are helping the Belgian-Dutch bank, as the first European banking institution in distress following the snowball effect of the credit market crisis in the United States, by partially nationalising it. The three countries support this financial and insurance institution with interest in Hungary in the amount of EUR 11.2 billion.
This weekend, the Belgian, Luxembourg and Dutch governments agreed, at the highest level, on this matter, also calling on the European Central Bank and the European Commission's competition officer.
In the euro area, the first major crisis in the context of the international financial crisis, which has been intensifying for more than a year, is for Fortis Bank. From a certain point of view, the decisions that will be taken in the case of Fortis Bank will serve as a precedent.
According to the decision made on Sunday night, the three states will buy almost half (at 49%) of the bank's capital in each country.
The bank is undoubtedly going to sell part of its holdings, among which, in the first place, the activities, mainly insurance, which it acquired last year from the Dutch organisation ABN Amro.
Last week, Fortis shares began a dizzying fall. In the second half of the week, serious signs of crisis have already been revealed at the bank.
Analysts agree that with its 85,000 employees, the bank is far too large to let it go bankrupt.
Only Friday, the company's shares fell by 12 percent, to reach its lowest level 14 years ago.
Since January, shares have fallen by more than two thirds of their value.
Taking into account the present value of the shares, the total value of the group's capital is around EUR 14 billion, which, according to the company's managers, is not realistic.
The company's management accuses the uncertainty of overseas, in relation to the adoption of the US $700 billion rescue plan, to be the cause of the fall of Fortis shares.
On Monday, the papers have already received a slight increase.
On Friday, Filip Dierckx was appointed head of the bank, as the new Director General.
The financial institution was also looking for private buyers, but has not yet received a proposal on the merits.
Previously, the Belgian government announced that investors should not worry, they would not lose their money.
No panic was felt in the bank's customer circle and no agency was stormed.
In Hungary, Fortis owns independent agencies and has also bought leasing companies.
A fox in the henhouse
In America, life and health insurance companies frequently refuse to sign an insurance contract with a candidate, based on information about their drug purchases.
Information protection experts fear that the data market will become uncontrollable.
"There are data protection programmes which link the use of information concerning the prescription of medicinal products, in all cases, to the consent of the person concerned.
This kind of program must be in independent hands, otherwise it means entrusting his henhouse to a fox" - recalled Richard Dicket, the creator of the program used to manage prescriptions for drugs, at the Washington Post.
Insurance companies make insurance premiums and capital insured in the event of damage, the health status of the client present, and if they feel that the risk is too great, they do not even ensure it.
In the past, they sent candidates for a medical examination, and they signed an insurance contract with them only after they learned of the results.
For the past ten years, Dick has found a much cheaper procedure: from an identification number, it is readily available from pharmacies, data on the purchase of the person's drugs in the past eighteen months. From this, the program itself determines, what disease the person suffers from and what his or her health is.
For example, if this person regularly buys high doses of cholesterol reducer, this refers to an extremely high level of fat in the blood, which puts it immediately in a higher risk category.
Several versions of this program are in circulation. Some determine at the same time a risk coefficient, so there is not much left to do to the insurer other than paperwork. However, tiny problems may still arise.
Some of the disadvantages of this program include the fact that a drug can be used for different purposes. For example, some mixtures can be used against migraine or heat flashes, but can also be effective against depression.
The latter is considered by insurers to be an aggravating risk factor, while the others are not.
Companies have developed in the research and analysis of data, and they must apply to the patient for authorization before collecting the necessary information from the pharmacy.
From now on, they are forced to do so by the authorities, even if they have not been punished for their past failures.
Recently, some companies have also been processing laboratory analysis results and linking them with data on drug use, and in this way, they are able to provide an even more accurate picture of the patient's health.
More and more companies have access to data, and the control of use is becoming more and more difficult.
There is a separate law on the protection of medical data, but its scope extends only to practitioners and insurers.
A proposal for a law on the extension of the control circle of authorities concerning companies specialized in the provision of data is currently before Congress.
Dick Richard acknowledges that this is not enough and that is why he has further developed his programme, which would condition the transmission of data to the exclusive agreement of the person concerned.
It is another question whether the person concerned is really free to give his or her consent or not, since if he or she refuses, the insurance does not sign an insurance contract with him or her.
So, in the end, hens depend on the benevolence of the fox.
The global menu of Marseille
The European Union and India are increasing their trade by two.
Since the European Union and India are very important trading partners for each other, this theme also dominated the agenda of this ninth summit alongside other problems, largely global.
Today, there will also be a France-India summit, where cooperation in the field of atomic energy will be the main issue.
The European Union recognizes that India is a great emerging democratic power that should be given a broader right of speech in international affairs, but member countries have not yet managed to agree on their support for New Delhi for its candidacy as a permanent member of the UN Security Council.
They did not dwell too much on this issue yesterday at this 9th summit in Marseille.
The French President, Nicolas Sarkozy, as well as the current President of the Union, as well as Commission President José Manuel Barroso and the Head of Diplomacy, Javier Solana, welcomed the Indian Prime Minister, Manmohan Singh, with whom they agreed that in five years they would increase trade by two, which means an increase of about 100 billion euros.
Taking into account that between 2000 and 2007, trade in goods has increased from 25 billion to 55 billion, this does not seem to be a too ambitious target.
In this sense, they have legally harmonized the 26 bilateral agreements with India on civil flights, which will also allow air trade to flourish in the future.
India would like to sign a free trade agreement with the Union by the end of 2009.
Sarkozy promised to speed up the negotiations.
The aim is to balance the situation with India, which is the EU's first trading partner, and New Delhi, which ranks ninth among the EU's partners.
The summit devoted its attention to global affairs.
The Afghan and Pakistani situation had been strongly condemned, as well as all forms of terrorism, and the urgency of holding a United Nations conference on that subject had been mentioned.
The completion of the Doha trade cycle has also been called for, although both have a large share in the current failure.
The EU has confirmed that it remains faithful to the energy and climate programme, in particular that it would like to reduce its releases of toxic materials by at least twenty per cent until 2020.
India also agreed on this point, as well as the need for a global market at the climate conference next year, and to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 50 per cent by 2050.
They would also like to prevent rising food prices, and supported the convening of an international working meeting to discuss the financial crisis.
The Indian Head of State is now going to the French capital, where, at a bilateral meeting, he is preparing to sign an agreement on the peaceful use of atomic energy.
In Paris, it is hoped that French companies will receive orders worth EUR 20 billion for the construction of Indian atomic reactors.
According to news agency information, the agreement would cover 15 years.
