Found Steve Fossett's plane, the billionaire missing a year ago.
The wreck of Steve Fosset's plane, the billionaire who disappeared on September 3, 2007, while flying in the Nevada desert, was found.
The debris was found on a plateau 3000 metres above sea level, in the Sierra Nevada area of Mammonth Lakes, on the California-Nevada border.
Inside the plane, however, no human remains.
Madera County sheriff John Anderson oversaw the remaining doubts: "The plane was located, we sent a team, and now we have confirmation that it is the one on which Steve Fosset was traveling the day he disappeared," he said at a press conference.
The sheriff said no human remains were found on or around the plane.
In February, the 63-year-old billionaire was considered dead.
The U.S. Transportation Safety Office (Ntsb) reported that a few hours after the wreckage, a team of investigators sent to the scene, identified the aircraft: it was the Bellanca 8kcab, which disappeared on September 3, 2007, when Fosset took off from Yerington in Nevada for a three-hour flight.
Yesterday, still in California, not far from the Nevada border, some of Fosset's personal belongings were found by a couple around their Mammoth Lakes home.
These are two documents named Fosset, both issued by the Illinois Federal Aviation Administration, silver species and a sweater.
Fossett's search was interrupted a month after his disappearance.
The billionaire had gained a place in history thanks to a long series of records.
By the sixth attempt, he had become in 2002, the first man to complete the world tour on an aerostatic balloon: two weeks of solo flight.
Three years later, he had travelled around the world by plane and without stopovers.
Among all these records, also that of having stolen at 15,445 meters high, on the Andes, but with a co-pilot.
